{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654520"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:52:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:52:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18620"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18620"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0,0.33,0.05,0.57]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11352"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76473"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11352"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18620"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61970"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10269"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26346"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26353"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76473"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring aerobic respiration in skeletal muscle cells, glucose is completely oxidised to carbon dioxide and water. This process involves multiple enzyme-catalysed reactions occurring in different cellular compartments.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary site of NADH production during aerobic respiration?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Glycolysis","Pentose phosphate pathway","Electron transport chain","Beta oxidation","Citric acid cycle"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecitric acid cycle\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary site of NADH production during aerobic respiration. For each glucose molecule, the cycle produces six NADH molecules through the oxidation of various intermediates. This occurs in the mitochondrial matrix where the reduced coenzymes can readily access the electron transport chain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlycolysis\u003C/strong\u003E produces only two NADH molecules per glucose in the cytosol\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectron transport chain\u003C/strong\u003E consumes rather than produces NADH\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPentose phosphate pathway\u003C/strong\u003E primarily produces NADPH rather than NADH\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta oxidation\u003C/strong\u003E of fatty acids produces NADH but is not involved in glucose metabolism\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe NADH produced carries electrons to the electron transport chain where oxidative phosphorylation generates ATP through the proton gradient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The citric acid cycle produces the majority of NADH and FADH2 used in the electron transport chain during aerobic respiration.","Pyruvate dehydrogenase complex converts pyruvate to acetyl-CoA, which enters the citric acid cycle.","ATP production from glucose oxidation primarily occurs through oxidative phosphorylation rather than substrate-level phosphorylation."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61970"}},"que